All [651 seats](/List_of_United_Kingdom_Parliament_constituencies_(1983%E2%80%931997)) in the [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom) were, for some reason, deemed important enough to contest.
A mere 326 seats were needed for a majority – a rather slender margin, one might observe, for the weighty task of governing.
[Opinion&#160;polls](/Opinion_polling_for_the_1992_United_Kingdom_general_election) prior to the event were, as often happens, less a crystal ball and more a funhouse mirror.
The turnout reached 33,614,074, a respectable 77.7%, representing a 2.4 [percentage point](/Percentage_point) increase from the previous election. A testament, perhaps, to the public's enduring belief in the democratic process, or simply a lack of better things to do on a Thursday.

