It's almost amusing, in a darkly comedic way, how consistently off the mark the [opinion polls](/Opinion_poll) were in the lead-up to polling day. Nearly every single one predicted either a [hung parliament](/Hung_parliament), with [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) emerging as the largest party, or a rather slender Labour majority, typically estimated to be in the range of 19 to 23 seats. Even in the final days before the nation cast its votes, the polls clung stubbornly to the notion of a very slim Labour majority. &#91;16&#93; Of the 50 [opinion polls](/Opinion_poll) released during the official election campaign period, a staggering 38 indicated that Labour held a narrow, yet clearly defined, lead. &#91;17&#93; The delusion persisted even after the ballot boxes closed; both the BBC and ITV [exit polls](/Exit_poll) continued to project a hung parliament, suggesting "that the Conservatives would only just get more seats than Labour." &#91;18&#93; A masterclass in optimism over experience, or perhaps, a fundamental misunderstanding of the electorate.

Given the overwhelming consensus among the polls that Labour and the Conservatives were running neck and neck in the final stretch of the campaign, the actual election result landed with the force of a genuine surprise for a significant portion of the media and, rather embarrassingly, for the polling organisations themselves. This spectacular failure of the [opinion polls](/Opinion_poll) to even approximate the actual outcome led to a thorough inquiry by the [Market Research Society](/Market_Research_Society), an organisation presumably dedicated to accuracy. This post-mortem analysis ultimately paved the way for the establishment of the [British Polling Council](/British_Polling_Council) a decade later, an attempt to prevent such widespread predictive blunders from recurring. Following the election, most [opinion polling](/Opinion_poll) companies re-evaluated and subsequently revised their methodologies, operating under the belief that a phenomenon dubbed the "[Shy Tory factor](/Shy_Tory_factor)" had influenced their results. This theory posited that a segment of Conservative voters, for various social or political reasons, were reluctant to openly declare their voting intentions to pollsters, thus skewing the aggregate data. A rather convenient explanation, if it allows one to avoid admitting a fundamental flaw in one's models.

### Results

•
See also: [Results of the 1992 United Kingdom general election](/Results_of_the_1992_United_Kingdom_general_election)
[Labour Leader Neil Kinnock](/Neil_Kinnock) conceding defeat. A rather poignant image, one imagines.
Results map. A colourful representation of political shifting sands.

The election turnout, recorded at a robust 77.67% &#91;19&#93;, was the highest seen in 18 years, indicating a deeply engaged, or perhaps simply easily swayed, electorate. There was an overall [Labour swing](/Swing_(politics)) of 2.2%, a movement that notably widened the gap between Labour and the [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)). While the [Conservative Party](/Conservative_Party_(UK))'s percentage of the vote only dipped by a marginal 0.3% compared to their 1987 performance, their [overall majority](/Majority_government) in the [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom) experienced a rather more significant reduction, shrinking from a comfortable 102 seats to a more precarious 21. This already slim majority was destined to erode further during [Major](/John_Major)'s subsequent term in office, plagued by defections of [MPs](/Member_of_Parliament) to other parties, a series of by-election defeats, and, at one point in 1994–95, the temporary suspension of the Conservative whip for certain [MPs](/Member_of_Parliament) who dared to vote against the government's European policy. By 1996, the Conservative majority had dwindled to a mere single seat, effectively rendering them a [minority government](/Minority_government) as they limped towards the [1997 general election](/1997_United_Kingdom_general_election). In 1992, the Conservatives secured an impressive 14,093,007 votes, &#91;19&#93; a total that stands as the highest number of votes ever received by any political party in a [UK general election](/List_of_United_Kingdom_general_elections), surpassing Labour's previous record of 13.98 million in [1951](/1951_United_Kingdom_general_election) (though it should be noted that the 1951 figure was achieved from a smaller electorate and represented a higher vote share). A total of nine government ministers, including the then-party chairman [Chris Patten](/Chris_Patten), unfortunately lost their seats in this election.

[The Sun](/The_Sun_(United_Kingdom)) newspaper, ever modest, famously declared its own pivotal role in the election outcome with the headline "[It's The Sun Wot Won It](/It%27s_The_Sun_Wot_Won_It)." However, in a rather belated admission during his testimony to the April 2012 [Leveson Inquiry](/Leveson_Inquiry), [Rupert Murdoch](/Rupert_Murdoch), the proprietor of [The Sun](/The_Sun_(United_Kingdom)), retrospectively claimed that the "infamous" headline was "both tasteless and wrong." &#91;20&#93; Curiously, [Tony Blair](/Tony_Blair) himself appeared to accept this narrative of Labour's defeat, subsequently dedicating considerable effort to courting and securing [The Sun](/The_Sun_(United_Kingdom))'s endorsement for his "[New Labour](/New_Labour)" project, both during his tenure as [Leader of the Opposition](/Leader_of_the_Opposition_(United_Kingdom)) before the [1997 general election](/1997_United_Kingdom_general_election) and throughout his time as [Prime Minister](/Prime_Minister_of_the_United_Kingdom) thereafter. A testament to the perceived power of the press, or perhaps a pragmatic acknowledgement of its influence.

Political commentator [Steve Richards](/Steve_Richards) observes that one prevailing theory for Labour's unexpected defeat hinges on [Neil Kinnock](/Neil_Kinnock)'s perceived triumphalism, specifically his appearance as "overconfident and cocky" at a major [Labour Party election rally in Sheffield](/Sheffield_Rally). At the time of this event, [opinion polls](/Opinion_poll) had indeed suggested Labour held a comfortable lead over the Conservatives. [Richards](/Steve_Richards) contends that this rally "acquired a mythological status as [a] fatal event" only *after* Labour's defeat, suggesting it became a convenient scapegoat. He argues that prior to the election results being known, "there was no suggestion that [Kinnock](/Neil_Kinnock) had made a terrible blunder" at the event. Indeed, [Richards](/Steve_Richards) highlights that the BBC's political editor, [John Cole](/John_Cole_(journalist)), had expressed admiration in his live reporting of the rally, even drawing comparisons to similar events held by [President Kennedy](/President_Kennedy). [Richards](/Steve_Richards) ultimately concludes that the party would have suffered defeat regardless of whether the [Sheffield Rally](/Sheffield_Rally) had ever taken place. &#91;21&#93; A rather inconvenient truth, perhaps, for those who prefer simpler narratives.

This election continued to highlight the [Conservative Party](/Conservative_Party_(UK))'s dwindling support in [Northern England](/Northern_England), with Labour successfully reclaiming numerous seats that had eluded them since 1979. The Conservatives also began to experience a noticeable erosion of support across the [Midlands](/Midlands), though they managed to achieve a slight uptick in their vote share in [Scotland](/Scotland), resulting in a net gain of one seat in that region. [Labour](/Labour_Party_(UK)) and [Plaid Cymru](/Plaid_Cymru) solidified their positions in [Wales](/Wales), as Conservative support continued its decline there. However, in the economically prosperous [South East](/South_East_England), [South West](/South_West_England), [London](/London), and [Eastern England](/East_of_England), the Conservative vote held remarkably firm, leading to relatively few losses in these areas. The constituency of [Basildon](/Basildon_in_the_1992_General_Election), in particular, became a symbolic battleground, often cited as indicative of a burgeoning "[nouveau riche](/Nouveau_riche)" working-class demographic, famously dubbed the "[Essex man](/Essex_man)," who were increasingly voting Conservative. This election also stands as the most recent instance in which the Conservatives secured more seats than Labour in [Greater London](/Greater_London), winning 48 seats to Labour's 35. &#91;19&#93; A stark contrast to the [1997 election](/1997_United_Kingdom_general_election), where the Conservatives would manage to win a mere 11 seats in the capital. &#91;22&#93;

For the [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)), their inaugural general election campaign was, by most accounts, a reasonable success. The party had painstakingly built itself up from a "low base" following its rather tumultuous and troubled creation, emerging from the electoral crucible relatively unscathed. &#91;23&#93;

This election represented the second consecutive general election defeat for the [Labour Party](/Labour_Party_(UK)) under the leadership of [Neil Kinnock](/Neil_Kinnock) and his deputy, [Roy Hattersley](/Roy_Hattersley). Both men, predictably, tendered their resignations shortly after the election results were confirmed, paving the way for [John Smith](/John_Smith_(Labour_Party_leader)) and [Margaret Beckett](/Margaret_Beckett) to assume the mantle of leadership, respectively.

Several sitting [MPs](/Member_of_Parliament) who had been expelled or deselected by the [Labour Party](/Labour_Party_(UK)) and subsequently stood as independents, including [Dave Nellist](/Dave_Nellist), [Terry Fields](/Terry_Fields), [Ron Brown](/Ron_Brown_(Scottish_politician)), [John Hughes](/John_Hughes_(Coventry_North_East_MP)), and [Syd Bidwell](/Syd_Bidwell), were all ultimately defeated. In [Nellist](/Dave_Nellist)'s case, however, the margin of defeat was exceptionally narrow. [Tommy Sheridan](/Tommy_Sheridan), famously fighting the election from prison, managed to poll a significant 19% of the vote in [Glasgow Pollok](/Glasgow_Pollok_(UK_Parliament_constituency)), a testament to his local support, or perhaps to the public's fascination with unconventional candidates.

